{"title_page": "Geoffrey Lunt", "text_new": "''' Geoffrey Charles Lester Lunt''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MC}} (1885&ndash;1948) was an [[Anglican]] [[bishop]] in the 20th century.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=109-aa_1-1_1-2&cid=1-9-1-32-36#1-9-1-32-36 National Archives]</ref>\n\nBorn into an [[ecclesiastical]] family<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.recyclegen.com/archives/montg_coll/klm/lunt.htm |title=Genealogical website |access-date=2009-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223174621/http://recyclegen.com/archives/montg_coll/klm/lunt.htm |archive-date=2010-12-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and educated at [[Sherborne School|Sherborne]] and [[Exeter College, Oxford]]<ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d 1897-1990]] London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref> he was [[ordained]] in 1909. His first post was as [[curate]] at Christ Church, [[Clifton, Bristol]],<ref>[http://www.christchurchclifton.org.uk/ Church website]</ref> after which he was secretary of the [[Church Missionary Society]] for Public Schools and Young People's Work then [[vicar]] of St Paul's, [[Bedminster, Bristol|Bedminster]]. A [[chaplain]] to the [[British Armed Forces|Forces]] in France during [[World War I]]<ref>{{London Gazette |page=6468 |issue=30716 |supp=y |date=31 May 1918}}</ref> he was awarded the [[Military Cross]] in the [[1918 Birthday Honours]]. When [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|peace]] returned he became [[vicar]] of All Saints, [[Northampton]] then [[archdeacon]] of [[Egypt]]. From 1928 he was [[vicar]] of St Mary's, [[Portsea, Portsmouth]], the largest parish of the city.<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]1940-41 Oxford, [[OUP]],1941</ref> before his appointment to the [[episcopate]] as [[Bishop of Ripon (modern diocese)|bishop of Ripon]].<ref>''New Bishop Of Ripon Canon Lunt Appointed'' [[The Times]] Monday, 29 October 1934; p. 14; Issue 46897; col F</ref> He was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to [[Bishop of Salisbury|Salisbury]] in 1946<ref>''Ecclesiastical News Confirmation Of Bishop Of Salisbury's Election''  [[The Times]] Thursday, 10 October 1946; p. 7; Issue 50578; col C</ref> and died in post two years later.<ref>[[The Times]], Saturday, 18 December 1948; p. 6; Issue 51258; col G  ''Obituary Bishop Of Salisbury''</ref>\n\n==Family==\nBrother - Theodore Robert Woosnam Lunt (1879-1951)<ref name=\"Lunt2016\">{{cite book|last=Lunt|first=Theodore Robert Woosnam|title=The Story of Islam|url=https://archive.org/details/thestoryofislam00luntuoft|year=1901|publisher=United Council for Missionary Education|location=London }}</ref>\nHis wife was Lillias M Sherbrooke (1889-1980)<ref>their marriage appears on Peerage website.</ref>\nHis sister Mary Baskerville Lunt married Hugh Cecil Jenner (1872-1968) who was descended from [[Francis Lascelles]] (1744-1799) and the singer Ann Catley\nHis son Ronald Geoffrey Lunt (1913-1994) was also a war chaplain who served with 7th commando in Libya;<ref>{{NPG name|id=78387|name=Ronald Geoffrey Lunt}}</ref> and later the rector of Martley.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{NPG name|89413}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward Burroughs]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Ripon (modern diocese)|Bishop of Ripon]]|years=1935&ndash;1946}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[George Chase (bishop)|George Chase]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Neville Lovett]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Salisbury]]|years=1946&ndash;1948}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[William Anderson (Bishop of Salisbury)|William Anderson]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Ripon (modern diocese)}}\n{{Bishops of Salisbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lunt, Geoffrey Charles Lester}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Anglican archdeacons in Africa]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Ripon (modern diocese)]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Salisbury]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sherborne School]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Chaplains' Department officers]]\n[[Category:World War I chaplains]]\n\n\n{{ChurchofEngland-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "''' Geoffrey Charles Lester Lunt''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MC}} (1885&ndash;1948) was an [[Anglican]] [[bishop]] in the 20th century.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=109-aa_1-1_1-2&cid=1-9-1-32-36#1-9-1-32-36 National Archives]</ref>\n\nBorn into an [[ecclesiastical]] family<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.recyclegen.com/archives/montg_coll/klm/lunt.htm |title=Genealogical website |access-date=2009-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223174621/http://recyclegen.com/archives/montg_coll/klm/lunt.htm |archive-date=2010-12-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and educated at [[Sherborne School|Sherborne]] and [[Exeter College, Oxford]]<ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d 1897-1990]] London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref> he was [[ordained]] in 1909. His first post was as [[curate]] at Christ Church, [[Clifton, Bristol]],<ref>[http://www.christchurchclifton.org.uk/ Church website]</ref> after which he was secretary of the [[Church Missionary Society]] for Public Schools and Young People's Work then [[vicar]] of St Paul's, [[Bedminster, Bristol|Bedminster]]. A [[chaplain]] to the [[British Armed Forces|Forces]] in France during [[World War I]]<ref>{{London Gazette |page=6468 |issue=30716 |supp=y |date=31 May 1918}}</ref> he was awarded the [[Military Cross]] in the [[1918 Birthday Honours]]. When [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|peace]] returned he became [[vicar]] of All Saints, [[Northampton]] then [[archdeacon]] of [[Egypt]]. From 1928 he was [[vicar]] of St Mary's, [[Portsea, Portsmouth]], the largest parish of the city.<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]1940-41 Oxford, [[OUP]],1941</ref> before his appointment to the [[episcopate]] as [[Bishop of Ripon (modern diocese)|bishop of Ripon]].<ref>''New Bishop Of Ripon Canon Lunt Appointed'' [[The Times]] Monday, 29 October 1934; p. 14; Issue 46897; col F</ref> He was [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|translated]] to [[Bishop of Salisbury|Salisbury]] in 1946<ref>''Ecclesiastical News Confirmation Of Bishop Of Salisbury's Election''  [[The Times]] Thursday, 10 October 1946; p. 7; Issue 50578; col C</ref> and died in post two years later.<ref>[[The Times]], Saturday, 18 December 1948; p. 6; Issue 51258; col G  ''Obituary Bishop Of Salisbury''</ref>\n\n==Family==\nBrother - Theodore Robert Woosnam Lunt (1879-1951)<ref name=\"Lunt2016\">{{cite book|last=Lunt|first=Theodore Robert Woosnam|title=The Story of Islam|url=https://archive.org/details/thestoryofislam00luntuoft|year=1901|publisher=United Council for Missionary Education|location=London }}</ref>\nHis wife was Lillias M Sherbrooke (1889-1980)<ref>their marriage appears on Peerage website.</ref>\nHis sister Mary Baskerville Lunt married Hugh Cecil Jenner (1872-1968) who was descended from [[Francis Lascelles]] (1744-1799) and the singer Ann Catley\nHis son Ronald Geoffrey Lunt (1913-1994) was also a war chaplain who served with 7th commando in Libya;<ref>{{NPG name|id=78387|name=Ronald Geoffrey Lunt}}</ref> and later the rector of Martley.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{NPG name}}\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward Burroughs]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Ripon (modern diocese)|Bishop of Ripon]]|years=1935&ndash;1946}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[George Chase (bishop)|George Chase]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Neville Lovett]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Salisbury]]|years=1946&ndash;1948}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[William Anderson (Bishop of Salisbury)|William Anderson]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Ripon (modern diocese)}}\n{{Bishops of Salisbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lunt, Geoffrey Charles Lester}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter Colleg